=====================================================================
THE MECHANIC
=====================================================================
Foraging is its own roll -- not tied to a skill, not tied to a stat. Each region below has
a d20 table: every number 1-20 maps to a SPECIFIC ingredient, not a range or a band. Tables
are ordered so LOW rolls land on the rarest/best finds and HIGH rolls land on the most
common ones, matching how the rest of the system already treats a low roll as the good one.

GENERAL FORAGING (not hunting anything specific): roll d20 in the region you're in, look up
that number on that region's table, that's what you found. Quantity: 1.

TARGETED FORAGING (you know a specific ingredient grows here and you're hunting it): find
its number (N) on the region's table. Roll d20.
  Roll <= N: you find it. QUANTITY = (N - roll) + 1.
  Roll > N: you don't find your target. Whatever's at your rolled number is the GM's call
    to award instead, or nothing -- an empty afternoon either way.
This means rare ingredients (low N) are both hard to find AND scarce even on a good roll --
you can never roll below 1, so a target at N=3 caps out at quantity 3 no matter how well you
roll. Common ingredients (high N) are easy to find and can turn up in real quantity on a
good roll. No separate rule needed; it falls out of the math.

FOUND EVERYWHERE -- the same five ingredients occupy slots 16-20 on every table below,
since they're common enough to not need a region:
  20  Wheat
  19  Blue Mountain Flower
  18  Nightshade
  17  Thistle Branch
  16  Garlic

